(34, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Loren M. Matthes assists city, town and county officials in planning and financing government buildings, infrastructure projects, downtown redevelopment projects, parking garages, aquatic centers and educational facilities. Matthes also works on structuring incentive packages for industrial/commercial prospects and negotiating economic development terms with companies, developers and underwriters. These projects often use a combination of incentives and revenue sources, such as tax abatement, tax increment, local option income taxes and State grant funds.\n\nSince Matthes’ involvement with the first tax increment financing (TIF) revenue bond issue sold in Indiana in 1985, she has worked on hundreds of economic development and TIF projects throughout the state, developing a statewide reputation for her expertise in this area. She is frequently contacted by local officials and administrators, county auditors, and State agencies to provide advice and guidance.\n\nPrior to joining Umbaugh in 1990, Matthes worked for a national public financial advisory firm and was an economic development specialist for the City of South Bend.\n\nMatthes has served as a guest speaker for the Indiana Association of Cities and Towns, the Indiana County Auditors’ Association, the Indiana Economic Development Association, the Indiana Municipal Lawyers Association and the Ball State University – Center for Economic and Community Development. She has served on the board of directors of the Indiana Economic Development Association (IEDA) and on the IEDA Legislative Committee.\n\nMatthes is a Certified Independent Public Finance Advisor (CIPFA), graduated with honors from the University of Notre Dame and is based in Umbaugh’s Indianapolis office.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}lmatthes.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Indianapolis,IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1505', 'none', '', 'none', 'matthes@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'lmatthes', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(35, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Paige E. Sansone’s professional engagements include financial studies for municipalities that often determine the impact of levies, tax rates and assessed values based on changing local or legislative initiatives. In addition, she assists numerous taxing units with budget preparation and capital planning. She has been a guest speaker for many municipal and county events, such as the Newly Elected Official Training sponsored by IACT, the IMLCT Clerk’s Institute, and the County Commissioners Conference. She is also a featured instructor of the IACT-sponsored Municipal Management Institute.\n\nPrior to joining Umbaugh in 2003, Sansone was the assistant budget director for the Indiana Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF). Her primary focus at DLGF was local government budgeting and she was a voting member of the Local Government Tax Control Board. Before working for the DLGF, Sansone was the administrative manager for the Seymour District of the Indiana Department of Transportation (INDOT).\n\nSansone is a graduate of Indiana University with a degree in finance and a Master of Professional Accountancy. Sansone lives in Indianapolis and is based in Umbaugh’s Indianapolis office.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}pgregory.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1521', 'none', 'CPA', 'none', 'sansone@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'psansone', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(36, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jason G. Semler works on economic development, financing and utility projects. His economic development work involves developing diverse revenue sources, such as tax increment financing (TIF) and local option income taxes, examining taxing units’ assessed values and their respective abatements, and the financial planning associated with the issuance of both tax-exempt and taxable bonds.\n\nSemler has been involved in numerous governmental projects, including projects financed by bonds secured by ad valorem taxes, income taxes and food and beverage taxes. He also has assisted communities with their capital project planning efforts and analyzed the estimated impacts that recent and proposed property tax regulations could have on various clients throughout Indiana.\n\nHe is a member of the Indiana CPA Society and the Indiana Economic Development Association.\n\nSemler is a graduate of Ball State University with a degree in finance with concentrations in corporate financial management and financial planning. He joined Umbaugh in 1999. A resident of Noblesville, Semler is based in the Indianapolis office.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}jsemler.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1540', 'none', 'CPA', 'none', 'semler@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'jsemler', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(37, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Tom Traciak’s practice includes bond issues, grant funding, tax increment finance, rate studies and lease-purchase agreements for local governments throughout Michigan.  He has a particular expertise in working with governments experiencing difficult credit and revenue support situations and has a concentration in water and sewer utilities.\n\nPrior to joining Umbaugh in 2011, Traciak was president of ACI Finance, Inc. in Mason, Mich., a company he formed in 1996 that served local governments throughout Michigan with capital financings.  He has worked in accounting, budgeting and finance in both the public and private sectors for more than 30 years.\n\nTraciak is a graduate of the University of Michigan and earned his master’s degree in public policy and administration from Michigan State University.\n\nTraciak is based in the Lansing Umbaugh office.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}ttraciak.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Lansing, MI', 'none', '(517) 321-0110', 'none', '', 'none', 'traciak@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'ttraciak', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(38, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Since joining Umbaugh in June 2000, Deen C. Rogers has been involved with numerous professional engagements including financial studies for municipally owned utilities, not-for-profit corporations, regional water and sewer districts and conservancy districts. These studies quite often have involved the determination of utility revenue requirements, cost-of-service studies and the financial planning associated with the issuance of tax-exempt bonds.\n\nIn 2005, Rogers became a manager in the Accounting Services Group of Umbaugh and has been involved in the preparation of dozens of annexation fiscal plans as well as providing budgeting and fiscal planning assistance to many communities.\n\nA graduate of the Kelley School of Business at Indiana University in Bloomington, Indiana, with Bachelor of Science degrees in both Accounting and Finance, Rogers has also completed professional courses sponsored by the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, the Indiana CPA Society, the Government Finance Officers Association and other professional organizations.\n\nHe is a member of the Indiana CPA Society and the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}drodgers.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1538', 'none', 'CPA', 'none', 'rodgers@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'drodgers', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(39, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jeff Rowe provides accounting and financial advisory services for various governmental entities, including public utilities, associated with the issuance of tax-exempt securities for the financing of construction projects and the refinancing of outstanding debt. He has a considerable amount of experience in the area of rate-making for utilities requiring the development and restructuring of rates and charges for municipal water, sewer, stormwater and electric utilities.\n\nRowe has also worked with a number of communities to provide ongoing financial management services, including contract controllership services, the development of multi-year operating and capital improvement budgets, financial forecasting, maintenance of proper cash reserves, and guidance in the area of accounting and recording procedures.\n\nHe is a licensed Certified Public Accountant in the state of Indiana and is a member of the Indiana CPA Society, the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, and the American Water Works Association. Rowe is a 1997 graduate of Indiana University, South Bend, where he earned a Bachelor of Science Degree in Business.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}jrowe.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Mishawaka, IN', 'none', '(574) 935-5178', 'none', 'CPA', 'none', 'rowe@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'jrowe', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(40, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jesse Nelson serves as an independent financial advisor to Michigan school districts and local governmental units. He provides clients with options and recommendations that help them accomplish their financial goals.\n\nSince joining Umbaugh in 2004, Nelson has assisted clients in a variety of ways, including providing millage impact studies for improvement projects, capital improvement financial plans, School Bond Qualification and Loan Program (SBQLP) applications, bond issuance and utility rate and cost of service studies.\n\nA 2003 graduate of Butler University’s College of Business Administration with a Bachelor of Science degree in accounting, Nelson is a Certified Public Accountant. He is a member of the Michigan Government Finance Officers Association, the Bond Club of Detroit and the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.\n\nBased in Umbaugh’s Lansing, Michigan office, Nelson has been the guest speaker on the topic of school improvement finance at regional and annual Michigan School Business Officials meetings. He has also served as an expert witness in the area of school finance.\n\nHe and his wife, Mary, live in Holt, Michigan. ', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}jnelson.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Lansing, MI', 'none', '(517) 321-0110', 'none', 'CPA', 'none', 'nelson@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'jnelson', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(41, 1, 3, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Jeffrey A. Messer serves as an independent investment advisor in Michigan, Indiana and Illinois. He has 22 years of banking experience in Michigan, Indiana and throughout the Midwest with an emphasis on public funds banking and investments.\n\nAt Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services he provides investment and banking services to municipalities throughout Indiana and Michigan, including helping municipalities invest their municipal bond proceeds and operating funds. Messer has assisted municipalities in structuring more than $1 billion of municipal bond proceeds. He also led a team of bankers in creating two new successful municipal investment products.\n\nMesser joined Umbaugh in 2005. His group provides independent advice on investments in excess of $450 million in assets for school districts and local units of government throughout Indiana and Michigan and is responsible for bank analysis and RFPs for banking services for many Umbaugh clients.\n\nMesser also is responsible for the many services provided by the Michigan School Investment Association.\n\nHe writes weekly commentary for the Michigan School Investment Association’s Weekly Market Review and is often called upon to give presentations at various association conferences in Michigan and Indiana on investment-related topics.\n\nHe is a graduate of Indiana University.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_1}jmesser.png', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1531', 'none', '', 'none', 'messer@umbaugh.com', 'none', 'jmesser', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(43, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}cpletcher.png', 'none', 'Curt W. Pletcher', 'none', 'Some good and bad news came out of the recent legislative session for public school finance in HEA 1062, but the news could have been worse. The new law provides limited relief to certain eligible school corporations regarding protected taxes and debt restructuring. The one negative in the bill will change schools’ future debt service fund operating balance.\n\n  A brief summary of the changes follows:\n\n  <b>Debt Service Fund Operating Balance</b> – This portion of the law applies to all political subdivisions and changes the allowed operating balance for new debt issued after June 30, 2014. Previously, all taxing units were allowed to keep 50% for debt payments due for the next six months for the ensuing budget year. The current 50% level will remain for existing debt issued prior to June 30, 2014, or if the debt is incurred prior to this date and subsequently refinanced. For new debt issued after June 30, 2014, the maximum operating balance will be 15%. For future budgeting purposes and tax rate management, schools need to factor this change into the structure of new debt. We will discuss tax rate management in more detail in a future newsletter.\n\n  <b>Protected/Unprotected Taxes</b> – School corporations losing 10% or more in property taxes in their transportation fund are eligible to distribute property tax losses proportionately for budget years 2014 through 2016. The option is not automatic. Eligible school corporations must submit a written request for a certification by the Department of Local Government Finance. Even though an official form is being developed, we recommend submitting a written request now so you have documentation of submitting your request well ahead of the deadline.\n\n  <b>Debt Restructuring</b> – School corporations losing 20% or more to property tax caps are eligible to restructure debt without seeking approval from the Distressed Unit Appeal Board. The new process requires a public hearing and may be subject to a petition and remonstrance process if taxpayers request it. The law limits the amount of debt that can be restructured to a maximum of 50% of principal outstanding for debt issued prior to January 1, 2009. It is important to evaluate the debt restructuring option for its overall economic impact and consider the school district’s future capital needs and plans. \n\n  If you need assistance or have questions about any of the provisions of HEA 1062, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', 'none', 'Partner', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(44, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}drodgers.png', 'none', 'Deen C. Rogers', 'none', 'In its original form, SB 273 would have required annexation agreements between municipalities and owners of real property to be recorded and it attempted to clarify who can bind the remonstrators in a settlement by requiring signatures of the property owners or their representatives. It was a relatively simple procedural change for annexations. Through various amendments, it became something bigger and could have either totally eliminated annexations initiated by municipalities or added new layers of complexity.\n\n  This list does not include all amendments, but some of the amendments would have:\n<ul>\n    <li>stopped involuntary annexations – one amendment would have ended them permanently; another would have halted them temporarily while the issue was studied, although there was a broad exemption for involuntary annexations for economic development.</li>\n    <li>mandated a court to award up to $40,000 in attorney’s fees and expenses to the signers of a sufficient remonstrance</li>\n    <li>required county commissioner approval for a city or town to annex contiguous property for economic development during the proposed moratorium period.</li>\n</ul>\n\n  With those changes, the legislation became much more than originally written, and the bill failed to move forward by the smallest of margins. If the bill had passed as amended, economic development of many types might have been affected while the issue was sorted out.\n\n  As it often happens with legislation, we may not have heard the last of some of these proposed restrictions. Bills to restrict annexation were considered in the 2013 session, and it is probable additional restrictions may be proposed again in future legislative sessions.\n\n  So, if you are considering annexation, it could be to your advantage to act sooner rather than later when the process might be more restrictive and confusing.\n\n  However, annexations need to be pursued for the right reasons and with proper planning. Those perceived as “land grabs” without proper planning and communication tend to make people angry — and that gets the attention of General Assembly members.\n\n  Annexation can be an emotional community issue, so it is essential to build a strong case and communicate it well and frequently. With very few exceptions, annexations must have a fiscal plan that includes estimated costs for providing services, financing methods, a plan for organizing and extending services, voting districts and other information.\n\n  If you have questions about annexation, please contact us at <a class="" href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(45, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}lmatthes.png', 'none', 'Loren M. Matthes', 'none', 'As originally proposed, Senate Bill 1 would have eliminated all Indiana business personal property taxes (BPP). The bill was strongly supported by the Governor, the Indiana Chamber of Commerce and the Indiana Manufacturers’ Association as a way to make Indiana more attractive to business and industry.\n\n  The Indiana Association of Cities and Towns and the Association of Indiana Counties led a coalition, “Replace Don’t Erase,” to bring attention to members’ concerns that totally eliminating BPP could cause a $1 billion tax revenue loss estimated by Legislative Services (LSA). LSA estimated that $376 million would be shifted to other taxpayers. Coalition members asked for a legislative solution to replace the $687 million loss to local government.\n\n  The bill as passed was something in between, but the concept of eliminating BPP will be studied this summer by a Blue Ribbon Commission and may return in the 2015 legislative session.\n\n  SEA 1, as passed, provides several <span>options </span>to Indiana counties:\n<ol>\n    <li>A county income tax council may vote to eliminate the BPP tax for <b>all taxpayers in the county with less than $20,000 of BPP value</b> (based on acquisition cost).</li>\n    <li>A county income tax council may vote to eliminate the BPP tax <b>for all new BPP in the county</b>.</li>\n    <li>A designating body can provide <b>a 20-year “super abatement” on new equipment</b> for individual taxpayers at a designated percentage for each year.</li>\n</ol>\n\n  <b>Should you consider one of the options? And, if so, which one?</b>\n\n  As you would for any revenue change, begin by understanding the amount of business personal property tax that comprises your current tax base and your largest taxpayers. Reviewing the fiscal impact data for your county or taxing unit will show the estimated impact of option 1, and you can determine if that option is advantageous.\n\n  When looking at option 2, be aware that although eliminating <b>new</b> BPP does not create an immediate revenue loss, it potentially can erode your <b>future</b> tax base, especially when combined with tax caps. The idea behind eliminating <b>new </b>BPP is that the loss could be offset by a boost in real property tax growth if you attract more businesses to locate or expand in your county.\n\n  For option 3, be aware of the potential for “over abatement.” Because of rapid depreciation of equipment, a 20-year tax abatement will exceed the value of the new equipment, reducing the taxable value of the older equipment as well. This phenomenon already occurs when traditional 10-year abatement is granted on new equipment to a company that has existing older equipment (depending on the relative mix).\n\n  Options 2 or 3 also may have the consequence of eliminating the opportunity to capture personal property tax increment (TIF) to fund capital incentives or infrastructure for business growth.\n\n  Umbaugh can assist with your analysis and help you understand potential short and long-term impacts when considering any of these options.\n\n  If you have questions or need help, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'No', 'none', '', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(46, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}pgregory.png', 'none', 'Paige E. Sansone', 'none', 'The traditional listings of local government budgets that dominate newspaper legal ads in August and September will soon be a thing of the past. However, we need to get through this year before we completely eliminate newspaper advertising from the budget process. The publication requirements that applied to the 2014 budgets also apply this year for 2015 budgets. \n\n  A change for this year’s budget preparation for 2015 (which also applies to next year’s preparation for 2016) is that each county is required to publish a notice stating the Internet address where local taxing units’ budget information is available and the telephone number for taxpayers to request copies. The county notice with the Internet address and phone number is required for the 2015 and 2016 budgets only. Counties will be allowed to seek reimbursement from taxing units for the cost of the notice. \n\n  Beginning in 2015 for the 2016 budgets, local taxing units will no longer advertise budgets, but will instead upload budget information to the Gateway Internet System. Taxpayers will have the ability to access and search budget data in Gateway. \n\n  If you have questions or need assistance with budgeting or financial planning, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', 'none', 'Principal', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(47, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Umbaugh Announcements', 'none', 'A number of bills intended to benefit Indiana taxpayers and communities could create new fiscal impacts on Indiana schools, counties, cities and towns. In some cases, those bills also have unintended consequences. The bills listed below are particularly pertinent to local governments, redevelopment commissions, utilities and schools:\n<ul>\n    <li><b>SEA 1</b> provides new options to Indiana counties for reducing business personal property taxes.</li>\n    <li><b>SEA 118</b> impacts redevelopment commissions and TIF and generally increases oversight and control by the legislative body.</li>\n    <li><b>HEA 1062</b> provides limited relief to certain eligible school corporations regarding protected taxes and debt restructuring. HEA 1062 also limits the debt service fund operating balance, which will affect all property tax debt issuers.</li>\n    <li><b>HEA 1187</b> deals with settling sewer and water territorial disputes outside municipal boundaries.</li>\n    <li><b>HB 273</b> would have impacted the annexation process and placed a moratorium on involuntary annexations. This bill did not pass.</li>\n</ul>\n\n  Look for upcoming articles in Umbaugh Footnotes that will delve into these bills and potential impacts and considerations. See the <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/senate-bill-1-a-compromise-with-options">article on SEA 1</a> included in this issue.\n\n  It takes some time after every legislative session to understand the fiscal impact of the final version of various bills. Some communities or districts will experience greater fiscal impact because of their unique circumstances. We look forward to helping you understand and analyze potential impacts on your community.\n\n  If any new legislation is of immediate concern to you, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>. We’ll be happy to address your questions at any time.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'No', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(48, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}jsemler.png', 'none', 'Jason G. Semler', 'none', 'How’s your local option income tax (LOIT) working out for you? Is it producing the revenue you had in mind? Will it produce the revenue you need going forward? It is good to analyze your rates and revenue from time to time to ensure that your LOIT is performing as predicted.\n\n  When Indiana’s property tax caps were enacted, a LOIT Property Tax Replacement Option was created as an option for county and local governments to reduce the amount of revenue lost to property tax caps. It was clear at the time that there was no “one size fits all” recommendation that works in every circumstance, because changes in taxes and revenue streams are interdependent.\n\n  The correct LOIT amount and whether it is most effective when distributed as a Homestead Credit, a Uniform Credit or Qualified Residential Credit depends on your mix of homestead residential (1% tax cap), agricultural and rental (2% tax cap) and commercial properties (3% tax cap).\n\n  Similarly, setting your LOIT at the full 1% allowed by statute is not necessarily the best solution. Since not all taxpayers are at the property tax caps, simply increasing the LOIT rate may not fully replace the revenue lost. The LOIT gets higher, but your losses to tax caps are not reduced as much as the LOIT goes up. For example, $1 million of LOIT revenue generated may only reduce $600,000 of circuit breaker losses. A public safety LOIT may be a better option to consider.\n\n  And, of course, the projections when Indiana’s property tax caps were enacted were based on a presumption that property values would steadily trend upward from year to year – a presumption that did not prove true over the last six years.\n\n  Five factors may prompt you to analyze your LOIT rates:\n<ol>\n    <li>Have your losses to property tax caps dramatically increased?</li>\n    <li>Have you seen or do you anticipate a reduction in local income taxes?</li>\n    <li>Has your mix of residential, agricultural and commercial land shifted since your LOIT was enacted?</li>\n    <li>Are local services are getting more difficult to fund?</li>\n    <li>The simple passage of time since your last analysis.</li>\n</ol>\n\n  If it’s time to review or adjust your LOIT rates, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', NULL, 'Principal', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(49, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}jsemler.png', 'none', 'Jason G. Semler', 'none', 'Jail crowding could be on its way to your county – if it isn’t already there. A new law that goes into effect July 1 changes the A-D felony sentencing grid to a new six-level grid. The goal of this change to Indiana’s criminal code is to reserve state prisons for high-level offenders, while providing lower-level offenders with treatment-oriented rehabilitation at county jails and through community-based correction programs and probation. We have yet to see the effect on county jail capacity and living conditions. What we’ve seen in the past is that when jails become overcrowded, the potential for lawsuits certainly increases.\n\n  How do you fund jail expansion when local governments are already struggling to do more on less money?\n\n  Counties can put a referendum on the ballot to raise property taxes for jail expansion. But with school referendums running about a 50/50 success rate, you can imagine how difficult it is to persuade taxpayers to vote in favor of funding jails.\n\n  As an alternative to property taxes, Indiana counties can use existing income tax revenue streams or implement additional income tax rates to address both capital asset and operating needs for correctional facilities. Counties can also consider other existing local revenue sources (such as a cumulative jail fund), or funds on hand. In doing so, it is critical to take an in-depth look at the County’s overall financial position.\n\n  Starke County took a slightly different approach in 2012. With assistance from Umbaugh, Starke County adopted an additional County Economic Development Income Tax (CEDIT) rate of sixty-five hundredths of one percent (0.65%) imposed on the adjusted gross income of county taxpayers. Doing this required getting enabling legislation from the Indiana General Assembly. In Starke County’s case, the legislation allows the county to implement the rate to provide funding specific to its correctional facility and still maintain the low property tax rates they considered to be not only important to their constituents, but also essential to economic development.\n\n  Starke County issued bonds to fund a comprehensive project constructing new jail space and renovating its existing facility to address current needs and the needs for the foreseeable future. It also gave them the additional flexibility to address the impact of the new sentencing grid. Construction started in the fall of 2013 and will be completed in 2015. The additional CEDIT tax is designed to provide sufficient funding to repay the bonds and meet the ongoing operating expenses as needed.\n\n  As the impact of the new sentencing grid becomes more apparent throughout the state, more counties will need to expand their correctional facilities and services. Funding them through additional income tax is an option worth considering. Because this option requires local meetings to inform your constituents, legislative action, and time for construction, you need to plan ahead to get the process started. This planning process should not only include what the current and long-term needs are for the county’s correctional facility; but also a comprehensive evaluation of your current financial position/resources, as well as the funding alternatives.\n\n  If you have questions or need assistance with expanding local correctional facilities and services, please contact us at footnotes@umbaugh.com.', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', NULL, 'Principal', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(50, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Christina L. Cromer', 'none', 'If you are an issuer of tax-exempt debt, there are 5 very good reasons to comply with the arbitrage rules of the Internal Revenue Code and related regulations:\n\n <ul class="no-bullet">     <li>5.<b> It’s a valuable project-planning tool</b></li>\n\n Periodic analysis not only keeps you informed of any rebate liability that is accumulating; it also provides valuable project planning information.     <li>4. <b>Increasing interest rates may increase your arbitrage risk</b></li>\n\n Recent bonds have been issued at historically low interest rates. As interest rates rise, the risk of generating positive arbitrage increases. Long-term funds, such as Debt Service Reserve Funds, are more susceptible to the risk of increasing interest rates.     <li>3. <b>Potential loss of tax-exempt status </b></li>\n\n The IRS could declare your bonds taxable if a failure to comply with arbitrage regulations was due to willful neglect. Even If the IRS does not make a determination of willful neglect, significant late filing penalties and interest can be assessed.     <li>2.<b> Increased number of audits and IRS questionnaires</b></li>\n\n Post-issuance compliance continues to be an IRS priority. The Tax Exempt Bonds office of the IRS Tax Exempt and Government Entities division has developed and implemented questionnaire projects over the past few years to evaluate and promote post-issuance compliance.     <li>1. <b>It’s required!</b></li>\n\n Tax-exempt bond issues are subject to arbitrage compliance from the date of issuance until final maturity or redemption of the bonds. </ul>\n\n  <i>If you have questions or need help with arbitrage compliance, please contact us at </i><a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com"><i>footnotes@umbaugh.com</i></a><i>.</i>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, 'Manager', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(51, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}dbaldessari.png', 'none', 'Doug Baldessari', 'none', 'Municipal tax-exempt bond interest rates are no longer at the historic lows we saw in the summer of 2013, but they are still favorable for financing projects or refinancing long-term debt for savings. Municipal bonds which have been outstanding eight or more years are likely able to be refunded for savings — or will be in the near future. \n\n  Bond interest rates have been trending down since the first of the year. Average bond interest rates for 20-year AAA-rated issues are currently hovering around 3.5%, and a shorter term issue is even less.\n\n  How long will these low interest rates last? No one knows, but many experts believe long-term interest rates will trend up as the Fed scales back on its quantitative easing program. \n\n  Your city, town or utility may still achieve interest rate savings by refinancing outstanding bonds or issuing long-term bonds for capital projects to take advantage of the current interest rate market.\n\n  <i>If you have questions or would like help to evaluate refinancing opportunities for your outstanding debt, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', NULL, 'Partner', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(52, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}jmesser.png', 'none', 'Jeffrey A. Messer', 'none', '<i>Part 2 in a two part series</i>\n\n  In <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/interest-rates-rise-as-federal-reserve-reduces-purchases-2">Part 1</a> of this series, we explained that the Federal Reserve embarked upon a program called quantitative easing, or QE, purchasing U.S. Treasuries and U.S. Government Agency securities to keep long-term interest rates low, stimulate consumer demand for mortgages and car loans., and increase the supply of money in the banking system.\n\n  In May 2013, Fed chairman Ben Bernanke first used the word “tapering” to describe how the Fed would begin reducing its monthly asset purchases, which were then at $85 billion.\n\n  Seven months later with the unemployment rate steadily improving and inflation under control, the Federal Reserve decided at its December 2013 meeting to begin the tapering process. The Fed<b> </b>announced it would decrease securities purchases by $10 billion to $75 billion per month. At the January 29, 2014 meeting, the<b> </b>Fed<b> </b>announced it would continue to taper and reduce monthly asset purchases by another $10 billion to $65 billion.\n\n  IMAGE HERE On February 1, 2014, Dr. Janet Yellen became the new chair of the Federal Reserve. She is a former Fed governor and is one of the chief architects of QE. In her first testimony before Congress on February 11, 2014, she reiterated a “steady-as-she-goes” policy, with a pledge to continue tapering as long as economic activity and employment continue to expand at their current moderate pace.\n\n  These are all indicators that the largest stimulative monetary program in the history of the U.S. is starting to wind down. The program successfully kept interest rates low at all maturity levels on the yield curve and helped our economy recover from the worst recession since the Great Depression. \n\n  What does the wind-down mean to units of local government?\n<ol>\n    <li>The Fed will have less of an impact on longer-term rates as long as tapering continues. The ten-year U.S. Treasury has recently been in a trading range between 2.60% and 2.90%.</li>\n    <li>Interest rates on checking and savings accounts and short-term CDs will remain at their extremely low levels because the Fed still controls short-term rates and has pledged to keep the Fed Funds rate near zero for an extended period.</li>\n</ol>\n\n  <i>If you have questions about how changing interest rates impact your financial planning and investment strategy, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'No', 'none', '', NULL, 'Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(53, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Christina L. Cromer', 'none', 'By now, many taxing units have received 2013 certified budgets from the State. If you are among the units that have unexpected cuts, there may be a way to restore some, or all, of your budget. Whether or not you can restore your budget depends on why it was cut in the first place. If your budget was cut due to insufficient funds, then the odds of getting the budget restored are slim. If the budget cuts were due to improper advertising or adoption, the odds are much better. \n\n  Taxing units may request additional spending authority from the Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF) through the additional appropriation process. The process consists of\n<ul>\n    <li>publication of a Notice to Taxpayers of a public hearing,</li>\n    <li>Council adoption of the appropriations after the public hearing, and</li>\n    <li>submission of the requested appropriations and other required documentation to the DLGF. </li>\n</ul>\n\n  The key to getting DLGF to approve an additional appropriation request is proof that you can financially support the appropriation. For example, if you request an additional appropriation of $100,000, you need to provide an estimate that there is (or will be throughout the course of the year) sufficient funding to cover your certified budget plus the additional amount you are requesting. The deadline to file additional appropriation requests with the DLGF is December 15; however, we recommend that you complete the process as early as possible. <i></i>\n\n  <i> </i><i>If you have any questions about budgeting, or if we can assist with the additional appropriation process, please contact us at </i><a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com"><i>footnotes@umbaugh.com</i></a><i>. </i>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', '', NULL, '', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(54, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}gmalone.png', 'none', 'Gerald G. Malone', 'none', 'After the crush of the final week of the Indiana General Assembly session, it takes a while to sort out what effect legislative changes will have on local governments. Some you’ll want to be aware of:\n<ol>\n    <li>The new money for roads in the budget bill is welcome news. Of the $215 million in new road funding for each of the next two years, about $100 million will be available to counties, cities and towns. The budget bill also adds the option of either a county council <b>or</b> a county <span>income tax</span> council being able to adopt a wheel tax. Following the County Option Income Tax (COIT) model, a county income tax council gives a voice to municipalities. The authority to form such a council begins June 1, but since wheel taxes for the following year must be adopted by July 1, you have a 30-day window to take advantage of this opportunity for 2014.</li>\n    <li> Every local government should be relieved that language was removed from Senate Bill 517 that would limited the amount of money for political subdivisions to keep in reserve for debt service to make half of the payment amount (three months’ worth). Since property tax payments to local governments sometimes run late, letting the reserves get down that low would surely have forced many localities to arrange temporary loans to make their debt service payments. </li>\n    <li>HB 1145 allows multiple ways for unused and unencumbered funds and unobligated cash balances to be transferred to your rainy day fund. It also gives redevelopment commissions more time to file annual reports with the DLGF and allows them to be filed by a redevelopment commission designee. </li>\n    <li>The IURC regulatory expansion of wholesale sewer rates in Senate Bill 385 is a double-edged sword. Wholesale users that are local governments will benefit from the new rules. Those that provide the service will not. It does reinforce the need for wholesale rates to be developed using sound cost-of-service principles. </li>\n    <li>House Bill 1307 makes it more difficult to purchase a utility owned by a private company. The lesson for local governments considering the sale of their municipal utilities is to be very cautious and consider the long-term ramifications of that decision. While you might receive cash for immediate financial needs, you give up your ability to control the quality of service and the rates charged to your citizens, and you may limit your ability to promote economic development requiring new capital investment. </li>\n</ol>\n\n  One trend we noticed in this session is the IURC being drawn into more matters. A few years ago, the circumstances in which IURC would have authority were reduced; now we see the pendulum swinging back the other way.\n\n  It’s also valuable to step back and think about what hasn’t been done legislatively that still needs to be addressed in future sessions.\n\n  Local governments will continue to deal with new requirements – including those of the Affordable Health Care Act — with stagnant and perhaps declining revenues caused by property tax caps and the lingering effects of the recession. The General Assembly passed a bill allowing Fishers and Cloverdale to enact a local food and beverage tax, but that fixes a symptom; it doesn’t address the underlying problem. Local governments still need new options in their revenue tool kits <b>and</b> the ability to make their own choices about what works best for their situation.\n\n  <i>If you have questions please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', NULL, 'Partner', 'none', '', 'none', '', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
