(59, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}lmatthes.png', 'none', 'Loren M. Matthes', 'none', 'A new bill (SEA 118) enacted in the 2014 Indiana General Assembly session increases oversight and control over Redevelopment Commissions and tax increment financing (TIF).\n\n  TIF can be a valuable economic development tool for Indiana communities because it provides a way to leverage private investment and to finance public improvements. When a TIF Area is created, all or part of the new <ins>tax</ins> revenue from that geographic area is captured for a fixed period of time to pay for incentives and infrastructure costs.\n\n  A Redevelopment Commission is responsible for driving and implementing redevelopment and economic development activities in a community. Redevelopment Commission members are appointed (and can be removed) by elected officials. Redevelopment Commissions help develop economic development plans, acquire properties for redevelopment, and negotiate financing terms and incentive offers for new and expanding businesses and developers.\n\n  Under the previous law, these economic development plans as well as the issuance of bonds and lease financings already had to be approved by the Legislative Body (common council for cities, town council for towns, and county commissioners for most counties). SEA 118 broadens the definition of obligations that need Legislative Body approval.\n\n  Perhaps, the biggest change is that SEA 118 gives oversight of Redevelopment Commission budgets to the Legislative Body. This change will likely lead to more formal annual budgets being prepared by Redevelopment Commissions, including more detailed project lists, TIF estimates and cash flow planning. The fiscal officer of the unit is the Treasurer of the Redevelopment Commission and is responsible for administration, investment and disbursement of all funds and accounts of the Redevelopment Commission.\n\n  Annually (before July 15th), Redevelopment Commissions are required to make a determination of excess TIF, and to pass-through excess assessed value to the other governmental units. Under the new law, if this excess TIF is greater than 200% of obligations, the amount of pass-through TIF may be modified by the Unit’s Legislative Body.\n\n  Another significant change in SEA 118 is that “Legacy” TIF areas created before July 1, 1995 will now have an expiration date. (TIF areas created after July 1, 1995 already have established expiration dates.) If you have a pre-1995 TIF Area, and would like to discuss ways to fund projects prior to the TIF expiration, we would be happy to discuss potential options with you.\n\n  Needless to say, Redevelopment Commissions will have to devote more time and attention to budget preparation and planning. Similarly it will become more important than ever to make accurate calculations of the estimated TIF revenue available for current obligations and future project needs to make sure they align. If we can be of help in this, please contact us.\n\n  Click <a href="/uploads/Increased_Oversight_for_TIF.pdf">here</a> for a summary of the bill changes.\n\n  <i>If you have questions about how SEA 118 affects your Redevelopment Commission or TIF area or if you need help with detailed budgets and excess TIF calculations, please contact us at<a href="mailto: footnotes@umbaugh.com"> footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'xhtml', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'No', 'none', '', NULL, 'Principal', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(60, 1, 4, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '{filedir_1}dhedden.png', 'none', 'Daniel A. Hedden', 'none', 'Many units in Indiana have seen comments on recent State Board of Accounts reports citing a lack of internal controls.  A common phrase in the audit is: &#8220;We found several instances where internal controls were deemed to be inadequate, which could impair the City&#8217;s ability to prevent and detect errors related to its recordkeeping.&#8221;   Scary words, but what do they mean and what can your unit of government reasonably do to improve internal controls?\nBy definition, an internal control system is an integrated set of policies and procedures to assist management in achieving its goals and objectives. Typical goals are providing a favorable control environment, continually assessing risk, developing and maintaining effective control-based procedures and ongoing monitoring of policies&#8217; and procedures&#8217; effectiveness. The policies usually spell out how potential problems will be resolved. In short, management promotes an environment that prevents and detects inadvertent errors.    \nExamples of effective internal controls include:\n<ol>\n	<li>Physical controls – Lock doors, lock safes, limit access, use passwords (other than 1234abcd), install (and actually use) alarm systems.</li>\n	<li>Define responsibilities – This will help address questions if there is a breach in procedures. Defining duties protects the individual and your unit of government.</li>\n	<li>Immediately document transactions – Generate a receipt, stamp received mail, create a register tape, review delivery slips, use pre-numbered invoices.</li>\n	<li>Separate related duties – The person handling cash should not also reconcile the bank account, use separate cash registers with separate access, the person who orders goods should not also receive the goods and approve the payment of the invoice, the person ordering inventory should not be the same person who counts inventory.</li>\n	<li>Supervisor review – Review the work of your internal resources and external consultants. If something does not make sense to management, seek an explanation.</li>\n	<li>Internal audits – Periodically verify a task completed by a clerk for accuracy and reasonableness. Document your tests and findings.</li>\n</ol>\nIn a small governmental unit, assigning different people to related tasks and having different people in charge of an asset and the asset&#8217;s recordkeeping can go a long way to demonstrate internal controls. The Indiana State Board of Accounts will need to see documentation of your control environment.  Written policies and procedures are helpful, but demonstrating that you adhere to those policies and procedures is better evidence of adequate internal controls.   \nIn summary, internal control shortfalls are a common finding in recent audits. Implementing a corrective action plan may be easier than you think. Separate your related duties, supervise your internal and consulting work and document your findings.\nIf you have questions, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.', 'xhtml', '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Yes', 'none', '', NULL, 'Partner', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(61, 1, 6, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'Increased Oversight for TIF and Redevelopment Commissions :: How to Improve Internal Controls', 'none', '[59] [increased-oversight-for-tif-and-redevelopment-commissions] Increased Oversight for TIF and Redevelopment Commissions\n[60] [how-to-improve-internal-controls] How to Improve Internal Controls', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'none'),
(62, 2, 7, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Umbaugh Announcements', 'none', '<em>Ten Steps to Investing Public Funds </em>\n\nWhen the banking industry was reeling in the first wave of the financial crisis of 2008, both the public and government leaders clamored for more regulation and more protection for investors and depositors.\nCongress heeded the public’s outcry, producing a raft of new regulations. The Dodd-Frank Act alone mandates 250 new regulations and 70 studies and created 13 new agencies, including the Financial Stability Oversight Council. The regulations impose higher capital requirements on the larger financial institutions and will ultimately result in higher costs for all banks.\nWhat happens when the cost of banking goes up? Banks will be faced with lower margins or may very well pass those costs along to their clients. But hopefully the additional costs and the effort required to comply with new regulations are a worthwhile investment to gain the new protections that have been put in place.\nAlthough the 10 steps to investing public funds outlined below are good advice in any situation, they have become even more important in the wake of financial industry turmoil and increased regulation.\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Identify your objectives </strong>–<strong> </strong>Just as you would in a personal investment portfolio, set goals for what you’re trying to achieve, but this time you’re using the public’s money. You need to assess how much risk you’re willing to tolerate and consider how liquid you need the investments to be. Think about your staff size and abilities. What is your capacity to oversee the investments? What amount of fluctuation can you tolerate and still meet your budget requirements? </li>\n<li><strong>Develop an investment policy – </strong>Now that you know your objectives, create a policy that helps you get there, by defining eligible investments, risks, management oversight, reporting, authorized financial institutions and maturity parameters.<strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Develop operational systems and procedures – </strong>Create written procedures to provide consistency, ensure compliance with public funds laws and describe who is responsible for various duties.<strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Prepare an investment cash budget – </strong>With a goal of determining “core” balances, identify dollars that can be invested for longer periods of time. These funds may include debt service reserve, rainy day, capital and various other funds. If you can invest them longer, it is possible to take advantage of higher interest rates.<strong> </strong><strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Analyze current market rates and develop an investment strategy – </strong>Contact your local banker, broker or adviser and ask about the current interest rate environment. Ask what the yield curve looks like and about interest rate trends. Get your adviser’s recommendation on how much and how long to invest. </li>\n<li><strong>Determine appropriate investments – </strong>The State has regulations and options for appropriate investments. These will be covered more fully in the next article.<strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Track investment results – </strong>As earnings reports come in; compare your earnings to your budget expectations. Also compare your investment results to what would have happened if you left all dollars in your bank sweep account.<strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Report results &#8212; </strong>Prepare a report once or twice a year so you are ready to report to your local board, council or commissions. Periodic reporting shows you and others the value of a more structured investment program. </li>\n<li><strong>Monitor and make changes as necessary – </strong>Some decisions you make now may not work as financial conditions change. Monitor your results to ensure cash budget requirements are being met and to evaluate if changing market conditions should alter your future decisions regarding amounts and length of time for investments.<strong> </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Institutionalize the process – </strong>Once you develop a structured and formalized system for investing your public funds, execute this process year after year to improve your investment performance and add additional dollars to your budget.</li>\n</ol>\nNext month, we’ll cover investment alternatives available under Michigan Compiled Law (MCL).\n<em>If you have questions regarding the new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at </em><a href=“mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com”><em>footnotes@umbaugh.com</em></a><em>.</em>', 'xhtml', '', 'none', 'No', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(63, 2, 7, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Umbaugh Announcements', 'none', 'In the last issue of Footnotes, we outlined the <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/banking-regulations-impact-pt-2">Ten Steps</a> to Investing Public Funds. Step 6 is to Determine Appropriate Investments. Consider expanding your investments by looking at all the safe options the public funds code allows. As the Indiana General Assembly reacted to the need to protect investors and depositors in these turbulent times for the financial industry, it created additional alternatives for investing public funds. Following is a list of eligible investments described in Indiana code 5-13-9.\n\n <b>Liquid investments</b> – Liquid investments can be immediately turned into cash. These are checking, savings, sweep, money market mutual funds, LGIP and joint investment funds.\n\n <b>Deposit Accounts</b> (checking, savings, sweep,) – Your goal for these funds should be to maximize interest and minimize fees. Calculate your net rate of return, balancing that with the reserve requirements and any high transaction charges and FDIC assessment fees. These funds have the advantage of being insured by FDIC and Indiana''s Public Deposit Insurance Fund (PDIF) or the new collateral requirements described in our <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/banking-regulations-impact-pt1">September 7</a> issue.\n\n <b>Repo Sweeps</b> – These accounts (Indiana Code 5-13-9-3) sweep dollars "off balance sheet" at the end of every day then collateralize your money with agency or treasury securities.\n\n <b>Local Government Investment Pool (LGIP) – </b>You may find it advantageous to participate in the Indiana State Treasurer''s Trust Indiana Fund created by Indiana Code 5-13-9-11. You can access funds the same day you request them. The Trust Indiana Fund invests in Indiana-eligible investments and 50% of the fund must be in Indiana bank deposits, but it can also invest in treasuries, agencies and commercial paper. No resolution is needed to deposit funds in Trust Indiana.\n\n <b>Interlocal Agreements </b>– Authorized by Indiana Code 36-1-7, political subdivisions can pass a resolution to participate in an interlocal cooperative agreement. These generally work like the LGIP and can only use investments eligible under 5-13-9.\n\n <b>Money Market Mutual Funds</b> – As described in Indiana Code 5-13-9-2.5, these portfolios are limited to direct obligations of the U.S., a federal agency, a federal instrumentality or federal government-sponsored enterprise or repurchase agreements fully collateralized by such obligations. There are minimum standards for credit ratings, and you may purchase them through your local bank or broker. \n\n <b>Short-term and intermediate investments</b> have maturities of 30 days to two years. These include CDs, CDARS, treasuries, agencies and municipal securities.\n\n <b>Government Securities – </b>These securities are backed by the full faith and credit of the United States Treasury, or are fully guaranteed by the U.S. and issued by the Treasury, a federal agency, a federal instrumentality or a federal-government-sponsored enterprise. They may be purchased through a local bank or broker.\n\n <b>Municipal Securities – </b>The ability to invest in municipal securities was added in 2010. These securities are issued by an Indiana local governmental entity, a quasi-governmental entity related to the State, or a unit of government, municipal corporation or special taxing district in Indiana. The investment is described in Indiana Code 5-13-9-2 and requires that the issuer has not defaulted on any of its obligations within 20 years preceding the date of purchase. They may be purchased through a local bank or broker. \n\n <b>Certificates of Deposit and Deposit Accounts – </b>State law requires the investing officer to obtain quotes from each designated depository in the political subdivision. In 2010, a section was added allowing the investing officer to place the deposit in the depository quoting the second or third highest rate of interest. Also the political subdivision''s board may pass a resolution allowing it to use Indiana banks outside the subdivision. This can be a valuable alternative if local banks are not interested in bidding on CDs. \n\n <b>Certificate of Deposit Account Registry Service (CDARS) – </b>This<b> </b>safe investment alternative for local governments was added in 2010. To use this option, your Board must pass a resolution or ordinance that allows it to use CDARS as an authorized investment. Many banks in Indiana are members of the CDARS network, and this form of investment is fully insured by FDIC.\n\n Once you determine appropriate investments, continue with the remaining steps to investing public funds to make the process work for you on an ongoing basis.\n\n Banks will continue to face regulatory challenges at the state and federal level, but by developing a sound investment and banking program, you can identify opportunities to safely increase your net interest earnings. \n\n <i>If you have questions or need help with complying with new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'xhtml', '', 'none', 'No', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(64, 2, 7, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Umbaugh Announcements', 'none', '<i>Second article in a series</i>\n\n In the last issue of <i>Footnotes</i>, we started this series by explaining that many new regulations have been created at both the state and federal level to provide more protection for investors and depositors in light of the recent crisis in the financial industry. \n\n Although the 10 steps to investing public funds outlined below are good advice in any situation, they have become even more important in the wake of financial industry turmoil and increased regulation. \n<ol>\n    <li><b>Identify your objectives </b>–<b> </b>Just as you would in a personal investment portfolio, set goals for what you''re trying to achieve, but this time you''re using the public''s money. You need to assess how much risk you''re willing to tolerate and consider how liquid you need the investments to be. Think about your staff size and abilities: what is your capacity to oversee the investments? What amount of fluctuation can you tolerate and still meet your budget requirements? </li>\n    <li><b>Develop an investment policy – </b>Now that you know your objectives, create a policy that helps you get there, by defining eligible investments, risks, management oversight, reporting, authorized financial institutions and maturity parameters.<b> </b></li>\n    <li><b>Develop operational systems and procedures – </b>Create written procedures to provide consistency, ensure compliance with public funds laws and describe who is responsible for various duties.<b> </b></li>\n    <li><b>Prepare an investment cash budget – </b>With a goal of determining "core" balances, identify dollars that can be invested for longer periods of time. These funds may include debt service reserve, rainy day, capital and various other funds. If you can invest them longer, it is possible to take advantage of higher interest rates.<b> </b><b> </b></li>\n    <li><b>Analyze current market rates and develop an investment strategy – </b>Contact your local banker, broker or adviser and ask about the current interest rate environment. Ask what the yield curve looks like and about interest rate trends. Get your adviser''s recommendation on how much and how long to invest. </li>\n    <li><b>Determine appropriate investments – </b>The State has both new regulations and new options for appropriate investments. These will be covered more fully in the next article in this series.<b> </b></li>\n    <li><b>Track investment results – </b>As earnings reports come in, compare your earnings to your budget expectations. Also compare your investment results to what would have happened if you left all dollars in your bank sweep account.<b> </b></li>\n    <li><b>Report results — </b>Prepare a report once or twice a year so you are ready to report to your local board or the State Board of Accounts. Periodic reporting shows you and others the value of a more structured investment program. </li>\n    <li><b>Monitor and make changes as necessary – </b>Some decisions you make now may not work as financial conditions change. Monitor your results to ensure cash budget requirements are being met and to evaluate if changing market conditions should alter your future decisions regarding amounts and length of time for investments.</li>\n    <li><b>Institutionalize the process – </b>Once you develop a structured and formalized system for investing your public funds, execute this process year after year to improve your investment performance and add additional dollars to your budget.<b></b></li>\n</ol>\n\n <b> </b>In the next installment of this series, we''ll cover investment alternatives now available under Indiana code.\n\n <i>If you have questions regarding the new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'xhtml', '', 'none', 'No', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(65, 2, 7, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none', 'Umbaugh Announcements', 'none', '<i>First article in a series</i>\n\n When the banking industry was reeling in the first wave of the financial crisis of 2008, both the public and government leaders clamored for more regulation and more protection for investors and depositors.\n\n Congress and the Indiana General Assembly heeded the public''s outcry, producing a raft of new regulations. The Dodd-Frank Act alone mandates 250 new regulations and 70 studies and created 13 new agencies, including the Financial Stability Oversight Council. The regulations impose higher capital requirements on the larger financial institutions and will ultimately result in higher costs for all banks.\n\n What happens when the cost of banking goes up? Banks will be faced with lower margins or may very well pass those costs along to their clients. But hopefully the additional costs and the effort required to comply with new regulations are a worthwhile investment to gain the new protections that have been put in place.\n\n Long before the current financial crisis, Indiana created the Indiana Board for Depositories, an independent body created to insure the safekeeping and prompt payment of all public funds deposited in an approved depository. The Indiana Board for Depositories maintains and operates the Public Deposit Insurance Fund (PDIF), which provides additional insurance for Indiana public funds not covered by insurance from any federal deposit insurance agency. Although the PDIF grew to $300 million, the banking crisis illustrated a need for another solution to protect public funds.\n\n The solution came in the form of new rules for collateralization covered in P.L. 115-2010. The new rules establish a method of placing banks in three categories based on their Highline Rating, which is a predictor of a financial institutions health and potential for failure. \n<ul>\n    <li>Banks in the lowest category (those with Highline Rankings from 0 to 19) are required to deliver U.S. Treasury Securities and agency securities to the State of Indiana sufficient to cover 100% of the amount of their public funds on deposit. Approximately 10% percent of Indiana banks are in this category. </li>\n    <li>Banks in the middle category (those with Highline Rankings from 20 to 39) must pledge or set aside U.S. Treasury and agency securities sufficient to cover 50% of the amount of their public fund deposits. Approximately 16% of Indiana banks are in this group. </li>\n    <li>Banks in the highest category (with Highline Rankings from 40 to 99) do not have special requirements, and this group constitutes approximately 73% of Indiana banks.</li>\n</ul>\n\n With these new protections, plus FDIC insurance and PDIF insurance, local governments can sleep at night knowing that their funds are safe with their local banks. If your local bank is no longer accepting deposits of public funds, however, this new law may be the reason why. The cost of providing the collateral to accept public funds may now be too much for them, especially when you add Dodd-Frank requirements and an economy still hovering on the edge of recession.\n\n In later installments of this series, we''ll cover 10 steps to investing public funds and eligible investment alternatives now available under Indiana code.\n\n <i>If you have questions or need help with complying with new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</i>', 'xhtml', '', 'none', '', 'none', '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', 'none'),
(66, 2, 8, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'gbawcum', 'none', 'George L. Bawcum serves as an independent investment advisor in Indiana and Michigan. Prior to joining to Umbaugh in 2006, he had more than ten years experience working with government entities and bond proceeds in corporate trust.\n\nAt Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services he is responsible for the analysis of cash flow needs of client bond proceeds and operating balances. He also structures, bids and monitors investments.\n\nOther responsibilities include construction accounting services for client construction projects and analysis of banking service requests for proposal.\n\nGeorge has a degree in Economics from Indiana University.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_2}gbawcum.png', 'none', 'Senior Financial Analyst, Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1509', 'none', '', 'none', 'bawcum@umbaugh.com', 'none', '', 'none'),
(67, 2, 8, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, '', NULL, 'jmesser', 'none', 'Jeffrey A. Messer serves as an independent investment advisor in Indiana and Michigan. Prior to coming to Umbaugh, he worked in the banking industry for 22 years with an emphasis on public funds banking and investments.\n\nAt Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services he provides investment and banking services to municipalities throughout Indiana and Michigan, including assisting municipalities with the investment of their municipal bond proceeds and operating funds.\n\nJeff joined Umbaugh in 2005. His group [or UCAS] provides independent advice on investments for local units of government throughout Indiana and Michigan in excess of $350 million in assets; and is responsible for bank analysis and RFPs for banking services for many Umbaugh clients.\n\nHe writes a weekly market update for UCAS clients and often gives presentations at various association conferences in Indiana and Michigan on investment and banking related topics.\n\nHe is a graduate of Indiana University.', 'xhtml', '{filedir_2}jmesserCAS.png', 'none', 'Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC', 'none', 'Indianapolis, IN', 'none', '(317) 465-1531', 'none', '', 'none', 'messer@umbaugh.com', 'none', '', 'none'),
